Introduction

why version control?

  • traceability of work progress
  • documentation

why version control?

  • clean working directory
  • non-linear development branches
  • robust, structured backups
  • progressive development

why version control?

  • collaborative work
  • reviewing
  • easy publication
  • openness

But:

  • annoying: there are so many files!
  • confusing: which is the latest version?
  • not progressive: did you fix that bug in the right file?
  • requires manual back-ups

git

  • a version control system
  • robust against errors
  • platform independent
  • geeky command line or user-friendly visual software
$ git

Workflow

Everyday git

  1. work on files

  2. commit to repository

    • adding files
    $ git add [file]
    • commit + message
    $ git commit -m "edit [file]"

Once in a while git

  1. tagging

    $ git tag [v*.*.*] -m "[newest version]"

  2. time travelling

    $ git checkout v1.0
$ git checkout master

  3. branching

graphical Clients

  • Windows: GitHub for Windows
  • Mac: GitHub for Mac
  • Linux: git-cola
  • all: GitEye, RStudio and other IDEs have plug-ins

many more: http://git-scm.com/downloads/guis

Exercises

1 | working locally

  1. create a git repository locally
  2. generate content
  3. add and commit

2 | tagging

in same repository:

  1. tag
  2. edit content
  3. add and commit
  4. check history: git log
  5. checkout tag
  6. return to latest version

3 | GitHub

  1. create a git repository on Github.
  2. clone to local Computer:
    git clone https://github.com/user/repo
  3. generate content
  4. add and commit
  5. push (requires password)
  6. edit online
  7. pull

4 | Collaboration

  1. clone shared project
  2. create a file
  3. add, commit, push
  4. assign an issue (i.e. a task)
  5. check your tasklist
  6. pull repository
  7. fullfill task
  8. add, commit, push
  9. check out progress on tasks

etc.: Milestones, Wiki

Final Thoughts:

Open source

  • turn private repos public!
  • choose a license: GPL or MIT for code, Creative Commons for text and data

Why?

  • scientific work is of public concern
  • enables re-use or inspiration
  • transparency adds credibility
  • scientific culture: acceptance of failure
